{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_elk_ver01/data/sn91068736/00296023188/1921011301/0104.xml":{"full_text":"ROCKINGHAM POST D1SPATOH, RICHMOND COUNTY, N. 0\n?AG SIX\nro:kingham\nPOST -DISPATCH\nPublished every Thursday after\nnoon at Rockingham. Richmond\nCounty, N. C.\nISAAC S. LONDON\nEDITOR ANi) PROPRIETOR\nOffice on Courthouse Square\nEntered as second-class mail\nmatter at the postoffice at Rock\ningham, N. C.\ncrs unaccounted for and 3,000.000\nwounded, whose deaths in li; years\nhave boon averaged at 10 per tout.\nMorrison Inaugurated. t\nWith bands playing, guns\nroaring and railroad whistles\nscreaming at intervals, Cameron\nMorrison was Wednesday at\nnoon formally inaugurated as\nGovernor of North Carolina. The\nceremonies were happily carried\nfollowing level: Attorney general j Qut in every detail. Ex-Lieut,\nfrom 03,000 to $4,000; state auditor I QqV m3X Gardner presided at\nfrom $3,000 to $4,000; secretary of\nstate $3,500 to $4,500; state treasurer\nAn act was passed by the Legisla\nture Tuesday raising the salaries\nof the constitutional officers to the\nDEMOCRATIC IN POLITICS\nI Correspondence from every sec\nI tion of the county inviled. Phone\ni 182 your items.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES:\nfWvear $2.00\nSix months\nThree mcnt'as\n$1.25\n.75\ni\nJOIJ WORK A SPKCIAI.TY j\nLjovc FLc Truck.\niif vVfirfoaboro has\nranee pro truc.k,\nbig machine\n;ei days ago. !t\nr at the rate ol\nite through its\nWade\nthe town\nstalled a now L\ncosting W2.0I 3.\naeachod Wade3l\nwill d: tcharge\nRflO ora '.ons per\ntwo itostea.\nHar let has hail a line largo trr.ik\nf -1 ni;r own beloved\n101 hi-\ntown 61 ;;oekin;rl.ar i- the host town\nof all- -continues with the make-'\nshift Ford.\nSor.'.' of those days the \"I told you\nsoV will wag their heads ami roll\ntheir predictions as a sweet morsel.\nOur town should get better protec\ntion ere a real conflagration results.\nAnd in getting a fire equipment, wo\nshould at the same time look to out\nwater supply-h insure a proper\npressure, \"and sufficient.\nA bloodhound as a prevention for\ncrime, and a Are equipment that\nwill he effective, are two items that\nmeasure passed the house by vote of\nliT) to 4i.\nthe exercises at the auditorium;\nhe introduced Ex-Gov. Biokett\n$3,500 to $4,500; state superintendent j who in turn introduced Mr. Mor\noi education $4,000 to $5,000. Thc'rison. Chief Justice Walter\nClark administered tne oarn.\nI Tht inaugural address was\nstrong and clear, outlying a pro-\nj gj-am distinctly progressive. Mr.\nThe country will applaud Mr. 'Morrison is possessed of the\nqualities of a courageous advo\ncacy, and Richmond county is\nexpecting its son to be hailed as\na great Governor.\nHarding's announcement to have an\ninauguration of the simplest kind.\nIn that ho is but following the pre\ncede at of his illustrious predecessor,\nMr. Wilson. The Republican en\nthusiasts were plannii\nexpenditure cf pc;\nan inaugural r u\nsplendor. Now, how\nI wisely put Ids\nit, and has tic'ciUci!\nsion ahallibe simple.\nmil wlncli\naugurs\nson discontinued\nwill not he hold.\n13 :or a. huge\ni avhig\n1; great\ner, Mr. Hard'\nToot down on\n;at the occa\nAlso the in\nresident Wil-\noight years ago,\nEllerbe vs. Derby.\nEllerbe high school basketball\ntaam is out for laurels. The\nteam is practicing daily. On\nWednesday the team played the\nDerbv school team, an:l won by\nscore of 13-11. They play Hoff\nman school Friday.\nSchool Enrollment.\nThe enrollment in the white\ncity school todav is 639313\n,s boys, 326 girls. Of these 251 boys\niua office in tho Allen build I and 2Q2 girls, total 513 pupils are\nin the Grammar School; while\n62 boys and-64 girls, total 126\npupils are in the High School De\npartment, which is housed in the\nOpera House building.\nErc-Governor T. V,. Biokett h\nopenei\nin;: on West Martin street, Raleigh,\nfoi the practice of law.\nSchool Inspection.\nThe report of Miss Idell\nBuchan, the nurse from the State\nBoard of Health, shows that rapid\nprogress is being made in the\nphysical examination of the chil\ndren of the county. For the\nweek ending Jan 8th, the follow\ning white schools were visited\nC. BROCK\nThe Battery Doc\nour city conimii\ntwisty consider.\nsi oners should sen-.\nTo The Ford Owners.\nWe wish to announce that our\nctlr Pnnm will remain open\nGibson Mills, Bostick, New Hope, I u lf) m for the convenience\nee Dee. rimes, Paradise; uoiorea those desiring partg.\nPoplar Springs, Malee, Chapel jj Page, Jr.\nGrove.\nfelt,\nth\nunan\n.1\ndeprc\nThe deflation movehjenl \"deflated\"\nmuch faster than many anticipated.\nMany manufacturing industries\ntemporarily cloBed down, and the\nprice of practically everything a\nfarmer had to sell simply tell to\npieces.\nBut the clouds apparently now are\nrifted. Banks and, financiers gen\nerally state that the country has\npassed through its worst period of\ndepression and the upgrade should\nlie ahead. And only the rankest\nkind of pessimism can hold us back.\nAnd who wants to be a pessimist\nWhen every human instinct spurs us\non to optimism? Let's demonstrate\nour faith in the return of prosperity\nby recognizing the. fact that it is on\nthe way and by doing our share to\nward its maintenance in this com\nmunity. Let the watchword he prudent\nand economical production, wisdom\nin spending, and tho employment of\na systemtaic course in saving.\nA proportionate amount of the\nprosperity of the country belongs\nto the people of Rockingham and\nRichmond county. Let's get all we\nten and keep all we get. Other com\nmunities will be doing the same\n.thing.\nI No. children inspected 387\nwitn defective vision 8\nwith enlarged tonsils 14\nwith defective teeth 370\nA MASTERED FEAR.\n(From The Toledo tiled.\nGovci urgent officers in India com\npile queer statistics. For example,\nthey have recently reported that in\n1919 the' persons who came to their\ndeath bj snake bite numbered 20,\n73 and that, in the same 12 mr.nths.\n58,416 snakes were killed. Further\nthere is tho record of 1,10'J deaths\nby tigers, t69 by leopards, 394\nwolves, 201 1 y wild hoars, 185 by\ncrocodiles, 118 by boars. 00 by ele\nphants am! by hyenas.\nDog Lost.\nLost, a pointer bitch; liver\ncolored head and spot on rump;\nbalance white. Reward for infor\nmation leading to recovery\nJ. P. Little, Charlotte, N. C.\nThe population of continental\nFrance beforethe war was \"0,602,\n258. A raw eensus will be taken\nm r i i 4l..- -fKri ii 1\ni'ext year. Meanwniie, lib\nestimate for the present year, not in\ncluding war mortality, is 40,500.7)0.\nThe reduction of the population by\n4,000,000 from war causes, evidently\nincludes the latest returns from the\nafflicted civil population and Jcaths\nfrom wounds subsequent to the war.\nAt the end of the fighting tho\nFrench military loss was 1,337.001)\ndead, together with 425,000 prison-\nApples.\nDon't forget to come to the\napple house, near Farmers Bank,\nand get you a supply of those\napples while they are going.\nPrice right. Full measure.\nSpecial price to merchants\nBurkett Purnell.\nToW-\nPUSH\nROCKINGHAM\nWARD.\no. h Sri V i\njm. .j, l fMtTH,t;y T a r wm n m. ai i i t i e\nlift' -if..-'. A \"wsSt' i\n3 W fl\nIt is part of our bank's business to aid everyone in this\ncommunity by showing them the necessity of having money\nin our bank.\nYou MUST bank regularly a part of what you earn if\nyou ever get ahead and ever amount to anything.\nMoney is the measure of SUCCESS in any business or\nprofession. Give yourself a full measure of success. It is\nyour RIGHT to yourself and your DUTY to your family.\nWe invite YOUR Banking Business.\nBank of Pee Dee\nRockingham, N. G.\nGroup Teachers Meetings.\nDuring the present month five\ngroup teachers meetings for the\nwhite teachers of the county will\nbe held as follows:\nJan. 19th, at Oakridge school\nhouse, teachers from Marks\nCreek, Cognac, Marston, Spring\nHill, Cameron, Pates, Osborne and\nNanford.\nJan. 21, at Roberdel High School\nteachers from Pee Dee, Rohanen\nHoffman, Ledbetters1, Prospect.\nJan. 24th, at Zion, teachers\nfrom Blewett, Lewarae, Cordova,\nCrosland, Campbell.\nJan. 26th at Mclntyre school\nhouse, teachers from Baldwin,\nLittle's Mill, Exway, Hines, Cov\nington and New Hope.\nJan 28th, at Ellerbe, teachers\nfrom Paradise, Bostick, Gibson\"\nMills, Pankey, Norman, Derby,\nKey.\nTeachers are expected to dis\nmiss their school on their res\npective dates and assemble at\nthe designated Group Centre\nSchool by 9:30 a. m. The pro\ngram of the day's work at the\nGroup Centre School is as fol\nlows: i\n9:30 to .9:35 Preliminary Con\nference of teachers.\n.9:35 to 10:00 Opening exer-\newes.\n10 to 10:15 Primary Reading\nAssignment.\n10:15 to 10:45 Grammar Grade\nReading Recitation.\n10:45 to 11:15 Arithm e t i c\nSpelling, etc.\n11:15 to 11:45 Recess, Super\nvised Play, Physical Training etc,\nGroup School dismissed for\nthe day.\n11:45 to 12:20 Discussion of\nDaily Schedules.\n12:20 to 1:00 Lunch.\n1 to 1:30 Monthly Reports on\nCensus, enrollment and Daily At\ntendance. 1:30 to 2:30 Discussion of Les\nsons Observed.\n2:30 to 3:00 Discission of\n1 Management of Schools On\nyard, in marching and in\nSchool.\n2 Organization of school Clas\nsification of pupils.\n3 Impressive things 'about\nWGrk and life of group centre\nschool.\n4 School room equipment and\ndecorations and how secured.\n3 to 3:30 Discussion of\n1 Community club work.\n2 Parent's days.\n3 Literary Societies.\n4 Debates, Declamation Con\ntests and spelling matches.\n5 The use of the library,\nhealth, citizenship.\n3:30 to 4 Written test on\nChapters 7, 8, 9, Reading Circle\nBook.\nAnnie Watkins, Co. Supervisor\nL. J. Bell, Co. Supt.\nReport of the condition ot the\nBank of Pee Dee\nat Rockingham, N. C.\nin the State of North Carolina, at the\nclose of business Dec. 29, 1920.\nRESOURCES\nLoans and discounts.\nU. S. Treas. Certificates\nOverdrafts unsecured\nNorth Carolina State Bonds\nAlt other Stocks, Bonds and\nMortgages\nBanking House, $9,000.00, Fur\nniture and Fi